{
  "text": "Shoulder subluxation was demonstrated sonographically in 44% of hemiplegic shoulders in this study. This falls within the reported incidence of 17-84% [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Acute hemiplegics with subluxation (75%) were significantly more frequent than chronic hemiplegics with subluxation (15%). This agrees with previous reports that shoulder subluxation in hemiplegia is predominantly seen in the acute phase [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , which has been attributed to its self-limiting nature [CITATION_7] . The subluxed hemiplegic shoulders were characterized by significantly higher raw USS score (approximately 4 abnormalities per subluxed shoulder) than the non -subluxed hemiplegic shoulders (about 2 abnormalities per non-subluxed shoulder), suggesting that presence of subluxation is associated with more soft tissue injuries. This is in agreement with the findings of Ko et al. [CITATION_8] who reported that hemiplegic shoulders with abnormal sonographic findings suffered more severe subluxation. Other investigators have also identified subluxation as an important finding in hemiplegic shoulders [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
